Module 1 : Introduction to Arrays
What is an Array?
An array is a collection of elements stored in continuous (contiguous) memory locations.
Suppose you have marks of 5 students.

Without arrays

int a = 90;
int b = 87;
int c = 78;
int d = 95;
int e = 88;
This becomes impossible for thousands of values.
Instead

int marks[5] = {90,87,78,95,88};
Now everything is inside one variable.
Real World Example
Imagine a train.
Coach1 Coach2 Coach3 Coach4 Coach5
Every coach is connected continuously.
Array is exactly like this.

+----+----+----+----+----+
| 90 | 87 | 78 | 95 | 88 |
+----+----+----+----+----+
Each box stores one value.
Why Arrays Exist?
Computers need
Fast access
Less memory
Easy traversal
Arrays provide all three.
