📚 Array Masterclass (Chapter 1)
What is an Array?
Definition
An array is a collection of same data type elements stored in contiguous (continuous) memory locations.
Example:

int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
Here,
arr is the array name.
5 is the size of the array.
10, 20, 30, 40, 50 are the elements.
Each element is accessed using an index.
Why do we need Arrays?
Imagine storing marks of 1000 students.
Without arrays:

int mark1;
int mark2;
int mark3;
...
int mark1000;
This is impossible to manage.
Using an array:

int marks[1000];
Now you can access every student's marks using an index.
marks[0]
marks[1]
marks[2]
...
marks[999]
This makes programs shorter, faster, and easier to maintain.
Real-Life Analogy
Imagine an apartment building.
+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+
|101  |102  |103  |104  |105  |
+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+
Each apartment has:
A fixed position.
A unique number.
The same size.
An array works similarly:
+----+----+----+----+----+
|10  |20  |30  |40  |50  |
+----+----+----+----+----+
  0    1    2    3    4
Each element has:
A fixed position (index).
The same data type.
Continuous storage in memory.
Properties of Arrays
An array has these important properties:
1. Same Data Type
Correct:
int arr[5];
Wrong:
int arr[] = {10, "Hello", 20};
You cannot mix integers and strings in the same C++ array.
2. Fixed Size
int arr[5];
The size is fixed after creation.
You cannot later write:

arr[10];
To have a resizable array, use vector.
3. Contiguous Memory
This is the most important property.
Suppose:

int arr[5] = {10,20,30,40,50};
Memory looks like this:
Address

1000
1004
1008
1012
1016
Values:
+------+------+
|1000  | 10   |
+------+------+
|1004  | 20   |
+------+------+
|1008  | 30   |
+------+------+
|1012  | 40   |
+------+------+
|1016  | 50   |
+------+------+
Notice every integer occupies 4 bytes.
That's why addresses increase by 4.

Why is contiguous memory important?
Suppose you want:
arr[3]
The CPU does not search for it.
It calculates the address instantly.

Formula:

Address = Base Address + (Index × Size of Data Type)
Example:
Base Address = 1000

Index = 3

Size of int = 4

1000 + (3 × 4)

= 1012
The CPU directly jumps to address 1012.
This is why array access is O(1).

What is an Index?
An index is simply the position of an element.
Index

0 1 2 3 4

Value

10 20 30 40 50
Example:
cout << arr[0];
Output
10
cout << arr[2];
Output
30
Why does indexing start from 0?
This confuses almost everyone at first.
Suppose the base address is:

1000
Formula:
Address = Base + (Index × Size)
First element:
1000 + (0 × 4)

=1000
Second element:
1000 + (1 × 4)

=1004
Third element:
1000 + (2 × 4)

=1008
If indexing started from 1:
1000 + (1 × 4)

=1004
The first element would no longer be at the base address, making memory calculations less efficient. Zero-based indexing simplifies pointer arithmetic and hardware implementation.
